        <item>
			<title>Johan Braeckman - The Rise of Islamic Creationism</title>
            <link><![CDATA[http://pointofinquiry.libsyn.com/johan-braeckman-the-rise-of-islamic-creationism]]></link>
            <description><![CDATA[<p>Host: Chris Mooney</p>
<p>Over the weekend, I was fortunate enough to attend the 2012 World Skeptics Conference in Berlin.</p>
<p>It's important to keep tabs on our skeptical and freethinking colleagues around the world, and the challenges they're facing. And in this case, perhaps the most disturbing story out of the conference involved the spread of a new form of creationism&mdash;namely, Islamic creationism&mdash;in Europe.</p>
<p>It's a topic I've wanted to explore on the show for some time. So in Berlin, I stopped to speak with Johan Braeckman, who has been tracking the subject closely.</p>
<p><strong>Johan Braeckman</strong> is a professor of philosophy of science at Ghent University in Belgium, and his research focuses on philosophical issues in the life sciences, particularly evolution and neuroscience. He's the author of a number of books and papers, including, most recently, <em>Doubting Thomas Has a Point: A Guide to Critical Thinking</em>, coauthored with Maarten Boudry.</p>]]></description>
