			<title>Francesca Grifo - Science Under Obama</title>
            <link><![CDATA[http://pointofinquiry.libsyn.com/francesca_grifo_science_under_obama]]></link>
            <description><![CDATA[<p>When President Obama was inaugurated in January of 2009, he pledged to  &ldquo;restore science to its rightful place&rdquo; in the U.S. government. And true  to his word, the president promptly staffed his cabinet with  distinguished scientific leaders, liberated embryonic stem cell research  from the Bush era restrictions, and released a&nbsp; memorandum on  &ldquo;scientific integrity&rdquo; intended to reverse the kinds of problems seen in  the Bush years.</p>
<p>Since those days, however, the "scientific integrity" agenda does not  seem to have filtered through the federal government as hoped. And  according to a recent report in the <em>Los Angeles Times</em>, some  scientists are having problems in this administration when it comes to  speaking with the media, or having their research results properly  handled by their superiors.</p>
<p>To put these developments in context, <em>Point of Inquiry</em> called  upon Francesca Grifo, director of the Scientific Integrity Project at  the Union of Concerned Scientists. As Grifo explains, claims that the  Obama administration is behaving like the Bush administration did on  science are absurd. However, the administration must do more to deliver  on President Obama&rsquo;s pledge to restore science to its "rightful  place"&mdash;and move swiftly to address reports of scientific discontentment.</p>
<p>Francesca Grifo is a senior scientist at the Union of Concerned  Scientists and an expert in biodiversity conservation, and heads up  UCS&rsquo;s Scientific Integrity Project. She has testified before Congress  about scientific integrity and is widely quoted&nbsp; in the press on the  topic. Prior to joining UCS, she was at Columbia University where she  ran the Science Teachers Environmental Education Program.</p>]]></description>
