			<title>Eli Kintisch - Is Planet-Hacking Inevitable?</title>
            <link><![CDATA[http://traffic.libsyn.com/pointofinquiry/POI_2010_04_09_Eli_Kintisch.mp3]]></link>
            <description><![CDATA[<p>For two decades now, we&rsquo;ve failed to seriously address climate change.  So the planet just keeps warming&mdash;and it could get very bad. Picture  major droughts, calving of gigantic ice sheets, increasingly dramatic  sea level rise, and much more.</p>
<p>Against this backdrop, the idea of a technological fix to solve the  problem&mdash;like seeding the stratosphere with reflective sulfur particles,  so as to reduce sunlight&mdash;starts to sound pretty attractive. Interest in  so-called &ldquo;geoengineering&rdquo; is growing, and so is media attention to the  idea. There are even conspiracy theorists who think a secret government  plan to geoengineer the planet is already afoot.</p>
<p>Leading scientists, meanwhile, have begun to seriously study our  geoengineering options&mdash;not necessarily because they want to, but because  they fear there may be no other choice.</p>
<p>This week's episode of Point of Inquiry with host Chris Mooney features Eli Kintisch, who has followed these scientists&rsquo; endeavors&mdash;and their ethical quandaries&mdash;like perhaps no other journalist. He has broken stories about Bill Gates&rsquo; funding of geoengineering research, DARPA&rsquo;s exploration of the idea, and recently attended the historic scientific meeting in Asilomar, California, where researchers gathered to discuss how to establish guidelines for geoengineering research.</p>
<p>And now, the full story is related in Kintisch&rsquo;s new book <em>Hack the  Planet: Science&rsquo;s Best Hope&mdash;or Worst Nightmare&mdash;for Averting Climate  Catastrophe</em>.</p>
<p>Eli Kintisch is a staff writer for Science magazine, and has also  written for <em>Slate, Discover, Technology Review</em>, and <em>The New  Republic</em>. He has worked as a Washington correspondent for the  Forward and a science reporter for the <em>St. Louis Post-Dispatch</em>.  In 2005 he won the Space Journalism prize for a series of articles on  private spaceflight. He lives in Washington, D.C.</p>]]></description>
