			<title>Ian Rowland - The Cold Hard Facts of Cold Reading</title>
            <link><![CDATA[http://traffic.libsyn.com/pointofinquiry/POI_2010_02_19_Ian_Rowland.mp3]]></link>
            <description><![CDATA[<p>Ian Rowland is a Mentalist and Mind Reader living near London, UK.&nbsp; The  world&rsquo;s foremost authority on cold reading, he is the author of the <em>Full  Facts Book of Cold Reading</em>.&nbsp; In this book, Rowland has defined and  categorized the different types of psychic readings, and created a  taxonomy of cold reading techniques.&nbsp; Rowland was the first person to  lecture on cold reading to the Magic Circle and his book has been  described as &ldquo;the definitive work&rdquo; on the subject by Derren Brown, James  Randi, Martin Gardner, Teller, and Banachek.</p>
<p>Rowland is a prolific writer and a charismatic lecturer and entertainer  who has appeared on television numerous times and performed in many  countries around the world. Rowland performs better than the psychics.  He convinced an audience he was a psychic medium for ABC&rsquo;s <em>Primetime</em>,  and during a BBC documentary one of his psychic readings was rated as  99.9% accurate.</p>
<p>In this conversation with host Karen Stollznow, Rowland explains the  history and meaning of cold reading, and how and why it works.&nbsp; He  demonstrates how cold reading is a &ldquo;Win-Win Game&rdquo; and psychics are  &ldquo;right&rdquo; even when they&rsquo;re wrong.&nbsp; He claims that he can replicate <em>any </em> psychic ability.&nbsp; Rowland  recounts some of his performances as a psychic, tarot reader,  astrologer, and medium, and his &ldquo;miracles&rdquo; of spoon bending, psychic  surgery, and hammering a nail into his head.</p>
<p>Rowland also discusses the practical, non-New Age applications for cold  reading, and how these strategies can be used for law enforcement and  business, but why they probably shouldn&rsquo;t be used for romance.&nbsp; A  qualified yet reluctant spokesperson for skepticism, Rowland presents  his &ldquo;off-message skepticism&rdquo;, and shares his opinion of what he thinks  the movement is doing right, and what he thinks we are doing wrong.</p>]]></description>
